SQL - Structured Query Language.

Its a programming language

SQL to access the database


field attribute :


*NOT NULL
 
*DEFAULT

*AUTO INCREMENT  cannot be null

* PRIMARY KEY (AVOID DUPLICATE ENTRY FOR KEY)

	You can only have one primary key, 

	but you can have multiple columns

	cannot be NULL


unique key (AVOID DUPLICATE ENTRY FOR VALUE)

	You can only have many unique key,

	- can have null value

*unsigned - positive value

*signed - positive & negetive value	



Data type:

** number (lenght depends on type)

	
	tinyint: 1 byte (2^8)
	
	max range 127 means 
	
	1 byte (means 3 digit) 
	

	tinyint : 1 bites (1^8)
	
	smallint: 2 bytes (2^16)
	
	mediumint: 3 bytes (2^24)
	
	int/integer: 4 bytes (2^32)
	
	bigint: 8 bytes (2^64)
	

* String:
	

TINYTEXT

A character large object column with a maximum length of 255 (2^8 - 1) characters.

TEXT

A character large object column with a maximum length of 65535 (2^16 - 1) characters.

MEDIUMTEXT

A character large object column with a maximum length of 16777215 (2^24 - 1) characters.

LONGTEXT

A character large object column with a maximum length of 4294967295 (2^32 - 1) characters. 


VARCHAR has a variable max size M up to M = 2^16-1




* FLOAT:

create table:

decimal(65,30) | float (255,30) | double (255,30)

SELECT flb+flb, dba+dba, dbb+dbb FROM `test` 

cannot be unsigned

32bit single precision Floating Point number

accurate to approximately 7 decimal places

Decimal & double:

Full same just lenght is diffenent



DATETIME:

8 bytes for DATETIME


Timestamp:

4 bytes TIMESTAMP

use for track change

Supported range 1971 - 38

TIMESTAMP value converts from current time to UTC so need small space

TIMESTAMP data can be indexed 

Queries with DATETIME will not be cached but queries with TIMESTAMP will be cached.

DATETIME is constant while TIMESTAMP is effected by the time_zone setting


